  <section class="jsSummary hide">
    <p data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="1500" data-aos-delay="150">
      The goal is for the supervised learning model to be trained until it can find patterns and relationships between the input data and the output labels, so that when it is given brand new input data, it can use this “knowledge” to correctly label it.
    </p>

    <p data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="1500" data-aos-delay="150">
      Supervised learning models are useful for solving two types of problems:
    </p>

    <div style="display:inline-block;">
      <div style="float:left; width:48%">
        <strong>Classification problems</strong><br /><br />
        <p data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="1500" data-aos-delay="150">
          A classification problem is when input data is put into specific categories, such as when your email identifies spam messages and places them into a spam folder.
        </p>
        <p align="center" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="1500" data-aos-delay="150"><img
          src="/badge-assets/fake-news/svg/classification.svg"
          width="138"
          height="185"
          alt="Classification"
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
          data-aos="fade-up"
          data-aos-duration="1500"
        /></p>
      </div>
      <div style="float:right; width:48%">
        <strong>Regression problems</strong><br /><br />
        <p data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="1500" data-aos-delay="150">
          A regression problem is when the input data is mapped to a continuous output, such as when a company predicts the revenues for a specific future date.
        </p>
        <p align="center" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="1500" data-aos-delay="150"><img
          src="/badge-assets/fake-news/svg/regression.svg"
          width="138"
          height="185"
          alt="Regression"
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
          data-aos="fade-up"
          data-aos-duration="1500"
        /></p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </section>
